-- Amazon.com Q4 profit tops forecasts
-- 
-- Thu Feb 1, 2007 4:30pm EST
-- http://www.reuters.com/article/2007/02/01/us-amazon-results-idUSWEN342320070201

 

 LOS ANGELES  (Reuters) - Amazon.com Inc.'s ( AMZN.O ) quarterly net profit halved due to higher taxes and investment spending, but its shares rose 6 percent as it beat analysts' expectations and gave 2007 forecasts above Wall Street estimates. 


 Amazon posted fourth-quarter net income of $98 million, or 23 cents per share, compared with $199 million, or 47 cents per share, a year earlier. Sales rose 34 percent to $3.99 billion. Wall Street analysts, on average, had expected the company to post earnings of 21 cents per share on sales of $3.78 billion, according to Reuters Estimates. Tax expense equaled 22 cents per share during the quarter, while a year ago the company received a tax benefit of 9 cents per share. Operating income rose 20 percent to $197 million. The company had been anticipating operating income to range between $145 million and $235 million on sales of between $3.65 billion and $3.95 billion. Looking to 2007, Amazon gave full-year targets for operating earnings of between $355 million and $505 million on revenue of $13 billion to $13.7 billion. Analysts had been expecting revenue of $12.57 billion for the year, according to Reuters Estimates. For the first quarter, Amazon expects operating income of $82 million to $122 million and net sales of $2.85 billion to $3 billion. Analysts had been expecting sales of $2.77 billion, according to Reuters Estimates. The Seattle-based company, which began as an online book seller but is now the most popular e-commerce Web site behind online auctioneer eBay Inc. <EBAY.O, has seen falling profit margins and decelerating sales growth in recent years. Its shares rose to $41 in extended trade after closing at $38.70 on Nasdaq.